commentBody:
@Jeb Jones
In cryptics, 'oddly' could well be an indicator to anagram, just as 'crazy' or 'juggled' are. But it can also be, as it was here, a clue to use only the odd letters in a phrase. Our puzzle goes the extra mile and, after you've assembled the odd letters from your grid entry, you're left with a /clue/ to /another/ grid dntry
 Brilliant!

@sykofox
I definitely noted the "so-called" in the clue and thought it was a quite appropriate reminder of the inappropriateness of the label.

It was an important reminder to me of how they adopted customs of the settlers and why, and how it didn't work--and why.

@Barry Ancona

I get the paper delivered on Sunday but the content is from Saturday - the weekend edition as edited in Paris.  It includes both the Saturday and Sunday puzzles. 

In any case, I'm not sure when the puzzles are "put to bed"

@Selective Walrus 

AORTAL is not a spelling variant of atrial. It's referring to the aorta, not the atrium. 

(Amun vs Amon (vs Ammon vs Amen) is the unfortunate side effect of transliteration, and is one where, if it pops up in crosswords, I just put AM_N and let the crosses decide.)

@Dave

Good point.

I'm so old that when I went to Michigan State and Michigan they knew how to count to ten.

@Alex
I think that the no-rebus party sees the deviation from one letter per square as a betrayal of the fundamental structure of the crossword game. If you've got a bunch of letters crammed into one space, how can you apply the rule that a square contains the same letter across and down? That's the whole point of CROSSwording -- that solving a DOWN gives you a bunch of letters that can be used to solve their respective ACROSSes.

As a pro-rebusite, I find the variety puzzles amusing. Every time I see a new diversion, I'm eager to see how the trick will work in the grid with various words. My all-time favourites are Schrödinger puzzles, designed to support more than one solution on the same grid. But I can imagine a viewpoint that looks at that and is just frustrated beyond bearing: "I need one unique, definitive, clear answer."

@Ιασων

Not mean? Perhaps.

Not nice? Definitely.

@Tim In LA 

Hey, it's the infamous New York Times crossword. It has a reputation to uphold.

It humiliates me quite often, but I keep coming back for more. Sparring with an 800 pound gorilla tends to hurt a lot, but oh, that feeling when you do mamage to knock one out.

@Vaer
LOL I love a good puzzle but surely one of the qualifications for entertainment is that it holds our attention. I've been struck by how often people refer to falling asleep mid-puzz.
Of course, if you leap out of bed to get your Spelling Bee hot off the pixel-presses, then the somnia (I'm assuming that's the opposite of insomnia, no?) is understandable. But that doesn't seem to apply to most cases here. So what gives, sleepy heads?

@Nancy J. Not everything that makes perfect sense to you will make sense to other people.

Exactly like how not everything that makes perfect sense to other people will make sense to you.

Not picking on you, specifically. I just admire people who can admit when they don't understand or were wrong about something, and I hate how common it is on the internet for unhappy people to look down on those who do that.

@Matt

Look again at how F and W phrased the comment.  It was not "I didn't understand." but "This puzzle was lame.  The theme doesn't make sense."

I was responding to that.

@F and W

Jacob deGrom’s fastball is impossible to hit. 

He’s a lousy pitcher.

@Andrzej
@Jane Wheelaghan

So when you guys abandon the solve do you reveal the grid out of curiosity?

@Ethan S.
@Nora

In this case, you might want to say "he who Diehl-t it."

@Nancy J.
I see you're getting a lot of push-back (some of it mean-spirited, too!) but I also protested AORTAL.  I know it's legitimate, BUT it is not the term used in the USA.  (A nurse has commented on this at a later point.)  
Our daughter's heart defect was one of the "top ten" and severe of its kind.  For some months our lives revolved around "matters AORTIC"....as one might say.

@MB
Funny but when I look up aortal aneurism (sic) what comes up is aortic aneurysm, so it looks like you’re wrong on both those words.
Nice day to you too!

@MB et alia
...if she does, it WILL be referred to as an AORTIC aneurism.
That is the usage in American English.

@Jerry
Bicycling.
Although, on a pleasant Sunday afternoon in May, Riverview and Akron-Peninsula would be good roads on which to take the Harley.

@retired, with cat

I like your interpretation of the puzzle as a "tribute" to classic misdirects,
But it does make the theme a little less "odd", no?

@The X-Phile 

I have noticed that every time I use ChatGPT it seems to be trying to snow me.

Even more disturbing: it's getting better at humor.

@Jerry

Miles is a musical genius who led a fascinating life.  A pioneer in Cool Jazz, as you note, and in Jazz(/Rock) Fusion with Bitc#es' Brew.

He was much interviewed during his life, so there's a long history to look at.  I find it interesting to compare him to Bob Dylan, in the way that they both got frustrated with the stupid questions that (unprepared, uneducated) journalists would ask them.

@The X-Phile
I'll disagree. Charlie Parker hired Miles in 1945. I can only think of a couple of bebop trumpet players before him (Dizzy, Howard McGee, maybe Fats Navarro).
Comes down to how you define 'pioneer', but he qualifies in my book.

@Rich in Atlanta
Great theme. I hope someone sometime did the companion theme -- call it "Accentuate the Negative."
If not, let me start the ball rolling with PLENISHMENT.

@MaryEllen
So you're just gong to throw a hissy fit and not explain why?

Okay.

@momonjava
I read this as purely informational. When you're subjected to an Anconian icefall, there is little doubt about it.
🤨

@Bill (cont.)
I could of course, purchase an individual account to the OED, but that's very pricey, just to get one's Wordplay jollies.

Any suggestions?

@Bill
I have a one-volume compact-compact version (with magnifying glass) but no place to set it out. It will not fit on a bookshelf and lives in its box, and is only brought out for very special occasions.

These days, it is easier for me to solve on crosses and find etymological information from the comments than it is to lug it out.

@Eric Hougland

I just finished watching the film "Blue Moon" yesterday on Netflix about the lyricist Lorenz Hart. I haven't read the magazine list yet, but Hart may likely be on it. The list of his songs I found online is amazing. I remember, especially, the tunes from "Pal Joey" which I've seen more than once. (I always liked Kim Novak since "Picnic.")

The movie, however, is an amazing slog, but not in a bad way. It shows the complex temperament of the creative personality, and I was thinking that most persons of high creative (or other) achievement have to, by necessity, be "not like us" in temperament and drive.

@lucky13

The list is limited to living people, so sadly Lorenz Hart (whose work I love) isn't on it. 

I'm surprised that you didn't enjoy "Blue Moon." We've not yet seen it (tonight, maybe, if we finish dinner early enough)? But other reports on it I've gotten have been positive.

@lucky 13
Only living US citizens on this Times  list. 
A lot of people didn't focus on that and were upset about certain people who didn't make it. I was getting madder and madder when I didn't see Joni Mitchell on it. Whoops, Canadian.

@Vaer

Yes, a lot of people missed those two details.

The comments to the list article suggest that Joni Mitchell and Neil Young both became American citizens. I don't know if that's correct.

@lucky13

Thanks for the clarification. “Amazing slog,” even with the following phrase, did not sound like high praise to me. 

I have seen the trailer for Blue Moon and I know that Hart is upset (to put it mildly) over Rodgers & Hammerstein’s new hit (State Fair, isn’t it?).

@Lynn

It’s hard to say what you just did without sounding like “Back in my day, Sonny…,” but you did pretty well. 

I am so tempted in many of these posts to reply “Skill issue”!

@Darren
I think we get puzzles like this once a month because they are not at all impossible without lookups for a sizable number of us. I am far from the most accomplished solver here, but I found the solve smooth, got the theme in my second pass through the clues, and found the second half of each theme pair impossible to get without the theme, but easy to get with it. 

There has to be room here for both people who hate puzzles like this and people who live for them. Each constitutes a sizable percentage of the solving public, although there appear today to be more likes than dislikes for this one.

@HeathieJ

That's how I approached that one too. 

I know little about jazz, but bop is something I kind of understand. "Neo" seemed like a pretty reasonable prefix (and was all I could come up with).

@Ken Burk

You didn't like the answers or didn't get that the "oddly" trick?

The circled letters are the odd numbered letters (if you count the letters to that answer) and they were the clue for the following answer (the answer that says "oddly" in it).

@Jerry

Amen!

Ape and aper are the worst!! They bother me immensely every single time they show up clued in the mimicking way.

@Raj T

One's home can be referred to as a pad. Hey, come on over to my pad and we'll have some pizza.. 

Bird's nests are made largely of sticks, so a bird's home could be considered a sticky pad.

@Raj T

Here's a riddle.  What's brown and sticky?

A stick.

@acjones
"So-called" to me meant a scathing indictment of the phrase rather than an endorsement. In fact, that is how I have heard members of other First Nations refer to this. Not only to "so-called civilized," but to "so-called tribes." 

Even the members of those five nations still use the phrase in historical contexts. As a descendent of perpetrators, I would normally not use it, but coupling it with "so-called" seemed to me to be making an important point that the original clue in the magazine did not make.
